<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-direct-tangents-to-two-circles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Direct Tangents to Two Circles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Construct direct and transverse common tangents to two circles
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To guide learners to discover that exactly two direct common tangents exist for two separate circles, and that these tangents appear to meet at a single point on the line through the two centres.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Prepare a sheet with two pre-drawn circles of clearly different sizes for learners who struggle to draw their own. Circulate and prompt: <q>Does your line touch both circles without crossing either one? Can you find another such line on the same side? Where do your two lines meet when you extend them?</q>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Discovering Direct Common Tangents</title>
                <p>
                    In this activity you will draw pairs of circles and look for straight lines that are tangent to both circles on the same side.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using a compass (or by tracing two circular objects of different sizes), draw two circles that do not overlap and are not inside each other. Label the centres <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Try to draw a straight line that touches circle <m>A</m> at exactly one point and circle <m>B</m> at exactly one point, with both circles on the same side of the line. How many such lines can you draw? Record your answer in the table below.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Extend both lines you found until they meet. Where does the meeting point lie in relation to the line <m>AB</m>?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    The meeting point should lie on line <m>AB</m> extended, beyond the smaller circle. This is the external centre of similitude.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Repeat parts (a)–(c) with two more pairs of circles, choosing different sizes and distances each time.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write a conjecture: how many direct common tangents do two separate, non-overlapping circles always have?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    Exactly two. Learners should state that two separate circles always have exactly two direct common tangents, and that both tangents pass through the same point on line <m>AB</m> extended.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <title>Direct common tangent observations</title>
                    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Pair</cell>
                            <cell>Radius of circle <m>A</m></cell>
                            <cell>Radius of circle <m>B</m></cell>
                            <cell>Number of direct tangents found</cell>
                            <cell>Do the tangents meet when extended?</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>1</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>2</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>3</cell>
                            <cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the concept of a direct common tangent and teach the compass-and-straightedge construction step by step.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Confirm that everyone found exactly two tangents on the same side. Ask a learner to describe where the two lines met — establish together that this point always lies on line <m>AB</m> extended beyond the smaller circle. Introduce the term <term>external centre of similitude</term> for this point.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Work through the construction steps in the Key Ideas box below. Demonstrate each step on the board before asking learners to follow along at their desks.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Emphasise that the auxiliary circle (radius <m>R - r</m>) and the semicircle on <m>AB</m> are construction tools only — they do not appear in the final diagram.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A <term>direct common tangent</term> to two circles is a straight line that is tangent to both circles and leaves both circles on the same side of the line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Two circles that do not overlap and are not inside each other have exactly <em>two</em> direct common tangents.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Both direct common tangents pass through a single point <m>O</m> on the line through the centres, beyond the smaller circle. This point is called the <term>external centre of similitude</term>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Construction of a direct common tangent</alert> (circles with centres <m>A</m>, radius <m>r</m>, and <m>B</m>, radius <m>R</m>, with <m>R \gt r</m>):
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Draw the two circles with centres <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>) and <m>B</m> (radius <m>R</m>).
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Draw an <em>auxiliary circle</em> centred at <m>B</m> with radius <m>R - r</m> (use a dashed line to distinguish it from the main circles).
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Find the midpoint <m>I</m> of segment <m>AB</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Draw a circle centred at <m>I</m> with radius <m>IA</m> (this is a semicircle on <m>AB</m> as diameter). Use a dashed line.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Label <m>Q</m> as one of the intersection points of the semicircle and the auxiliary circle.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Draw the ray from <m>B</m> through <m>Q</m> and extend it to meet circle <m>B</m> at the point <m>T'</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    At <m>T'</m>, construct the tangent to circle <m>B</m> (draw a line through <m>T'</m> perpendicular to the radius <m>BT'</m>). Extend this tangent until it meets line <m>AB</m> extended at the point <m>O</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Draw a straight line from <m>O</m> through <m>T'</m> and extend it until it meets circle <m>A</m> at the point <m>T</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    The line <m>TT'</m> is one direct common tangent.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Label <m>Q'</m> as the other intersection point from Step 5. Repeat Steps 6–9 using <m>Q'</m> in place of <m>Q</m> to obtain the second direct common tangent.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <p>
        The diagram below shows the construction for two circles with centre <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>) and centre <m>B</m> (radius <m>R</m>). The dashed orange circle (radius <m>R - r</m>) and the dashed blue semicircle are construction aids; the two solid lines through <m>O</m> are the direct common tangents.
    </p>

    <!-- TODO: TikZ construction figure — tkz-euclide, A at origin, B to the right,
         show auxiliary circle at B (dashed orange, radius R-r), semicircle at I (dashed blue),
         intersection points Q and Q', rays BQ and BQ' to T1' and T2', tangent lines T1T1' and T2T2',
         external centre of similitude O on line AB extended left beyond A.
         Labels: O, A, B, I, Q, Q', T1, T1', T2, T2'. -->

    <figure xml:id="fig-direct-tangents-construction">
        <caption>
            Construction of the two direct common tangents to circles at <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>) and <m>B</m> (radius <m>R</m>).
            The dashed circles are construction aids only.
        </caption>
        <image width="75%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two circles centred at A and B. A dashed auxiliary circle at B has radius R minus r.
                A dashed semicircle has diameter AB. Intersection points Q and Q' are marked.
                Rays from B through Q and Q' meet circle B at T1-prime and T2-prime.
                Two tangent lines pass through the external centre of similitude O on line AB extended.
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
                \pgfmathsetmacro{\rA}{1}
                \pgfmathsetmacro{\rB}{2.5}
                \pgfmathsetmacro{\rdiff}{\rB-\rA}
                % A=(0,0), B=(4.5,0); represents r=2cm, R=5cm, d=9cm scaled by 1/2.
                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4.5/0/B}
                \tkzDefMidPoint(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{I}
                % Reference point on auxiliary circle (center B, radius R-r=1.5).
                % Intersect line AB with auxiliary circle; F is the right-side point.
                \tkzInterLC[R](A,B)(B,\rdiff) \tkzGetPoints{Eleft}{F}
                % Intersect Thales circle (center I, through B) with auxiliary circle (center B, through F)
                % gives the two intersection points Q (upper) and Qp (lower).
                \tkzInterCC(I,B)(B,F) \tkzGetPoints{Q}{Qp}
                % Extend ray B->Q to circle B; second returned point T1p is in direction of Q from B.
                \tkzInterLC[R](B,Q)(B,\rB) \tkzGetPoints{Xtmp}{T1p}
                % Tangent at T1p meets line AB at the external centre of similitude O.
                \tkzDefLine[tangent at=T1p](B) \tkzGetPoint{tang1}
                \tkzInterLL(T1p,tang1)(A,B) \tkzGetPoint{O}
                % Line O->T1p meets circle A at T1 (tangency, so double root; first point = T1).
                \tkzInterLC[R](O,T1p)(A,\rA) \tkzGetPoints{T1}{T1x}
                % Lower tangent: extend ray B->Qp to circle B; second point T2p in direction of Qp.
                \tkzInterLC[R](B,Qp)(B,\rB) \tkzGetPoints{Xtmp2}{T2p}
                \tkzInterLC[R](O,T2p)(A,\rA) \tkzGetPoints{T2}{T2x}
                % Circle reference points (distinct names to avoid colliding with intersection points above).
                \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rA) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rB) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rdiff) \tkzGetPoint{cAux}
                % Draw the two main circles (solid) and the construction aids (dashed).
                \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,cA)
                \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,cB)
                \tkzDrawCircle[orange,dashed](B,cAux)
                \tkzDrawCircle[teal,dashed](I,B)
                % Construction rays from B to Q and Qp.
                \tkzDrawSegments[gray,dashed](B,Q B,Qp)
                % The two direct common tangent lines.
                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.15 and 0.15](T1,T1p)
                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.15 and 0.15](T2,T2p)
                % Centre line extended to show O.
                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.8 and 0.1](O,B)
                % Points and labels.
                \tkzDrawPoints(O,A,B,I,Q,Qp,T1,T1p,T2,T2p)
                \tkzLabelPoint[below left](O){$O$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below](I){$I$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[above](Q){$Q$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below](Qp){$Q'$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T1){$T_1$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[above right](T1p){$T_1'$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below left](T2){$T_2$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below right](T2p){$T_2'$}
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Once the construction lines are removed, the result is two circles with two direct common tangents meeting at <m>O</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-direct-tangents-result">
        <caption>
            The two direct common tangents <m>T_1 T_1'</m> and <m>T_2 T_2'</m> to circles at <m>A</m>
            (radius 2 cm) and <m>B</m> (radius 5 cm), both passing through the external centre of
            similitude <m>O</m>.
        </caption>
        <image width="70%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two circles centred at A and B. Two straight lines each touch both circles and
                meet at the external centre of similitude O on line AB extended beyond A.
                The four tangent points T1, T1-prime, T2, T2-prime are marked.
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
                \pgfmathsetmacro{\rA}{1}
                \pgfmathsetmacro{\rB}{2.5}
                % A=(0,0), B=(4.5,0), O=(-3,0); represents r=2cm, R=5cm, d=9cm scaled by 1/2.
                \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 4.5/0/B, -3/0/O}
                \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rA) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rB) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                % Tangent points from O to each circle via the circle-on-diameter method.
                % For circle A: T1 and T2 lie on both circle A and the circle with diameter OA.
                \tkzDefMidPoint(O,A) \tkzGetPoint{MA}
                \tkzInterCC(MA,A)(A,cA) \tkzGetPoints{T1}{T2}
                % For circle B: T1p and T2p via circle with diameter OB.
                \tkzDefMidPoint(O,B) \tkzGetPoint{MB}
                \tkzInterCC(MB,B)(B,cB) \tkzGetPoints{T1p}{T2p}
                % Draw circles and tangent lines.
                \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,cA)
                \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,cB)
                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.25 and 0.15](T1,T1p)
                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.25 and 0.15](T2,T2p)
                \tkzDrawLine[add=0.8 and 0.1](O,B)
                % Points and labels.
                \tkzDrawPoints(O,A,B,T1,T1p,T2,T2p)
                \tkzLabelPoint[below left](O){$O$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T1){$T_1$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[above right](T1p){$T_1'$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below left](T2){$T_2$}
                \tkzLabelPoint[below right](T2p){$T_2'$}
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example xml:id="ex-direct-tangent-construction">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Two circles have centres <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> with radii 2 cm and 5 cm respectively. The distance <m>AB = 9</m> cm. Using a compass and ruler, construct the direct common tangents to the two circles.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Follow the construction steps from the Key Ideas box above.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw circle <m>A</m> with radius 2 cm and circle <m>B</m> with radius 5 cm, with <m>AB = 9</m> cm.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Set your compass to <m>R - r = 5 - 2 = 3</m> cm. Draw an auxiliary circle centred at <m>B</m> with radius 3 cm (dashed).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Bisect <m>AB</m> to find the midpoint <m>I</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Set your compass to <m>IA = IB = 4.5</m> cm. Draw the semicircle on diameter <m>AB</m> (dashed).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Mark the two intersection points <m>Q</m> and <m>Q'</m> of the semicircle and the auxiliary circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw the ray <m>BQ</m> extended to meet circle <m>B</m> at <m>T_1'</m>. Construct the tangent to circle <m>B</m> at <m>T_1'</m>; extend it to meet line <m>AB</m> extended at <m>O</m>. Draw line <m>OT_1'</m> extended to meet circle <m>A</m> at <m>T_1</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Repeat using <m>Q'</m> to find the second tangent <m>T_2 T_2'</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>The completed diagram is shown in <xref ref="fig-direct-tangents-result"/>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-direct-tangent-length">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Two circles have their centres 13 cm apart. Their radii are 2 cm and 7 cm. Calculate the length of a direct common tangent.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let the centres be <m>A</m> (radius <m>r = 2</m> cm) and <m>B</m> (radius <m>R = 7</m> cm), with <m>AB = d = 13</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                Draw a line through <m>A</m> parallel to the tangent <m>TT'</m>, meeting the perpendicular <m>BT'</m> at the point <m>M</m>. This creates a right triangle with:
                <ul>
                    <li><p>hypotenuse <m>AB = 13</m> cm,</p></li>
                    <li><p>one leg <m>BM = R - r = 7 - 2 = 5</m> cm,</p></li>
                    <li><p>other leg <m>AM = TT'</m> (the length we want).</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-direct-tangent-formula">
                <caption>
                    The right triangle <m>ABM</m> used to derive the tangent length formula.
                    Here <m>r = 2</m> cm, <m>R = 7</m> cm, <m>d = 13</m> cm.
                </caption>
                <image width="75%">
                    <shortdescription>
                        Circles at A and B with a direct common tangent TT-prime. A dashed line
                        from A parallel to the tangent meets the radius BT-prime at M, forming
                        right triangle ABM with the right angle at M.
                    </shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                        % Scaled by 0.5: r=1 (=2cm), R=3.5 (=7cm), d=6.5 (=13cm).
                        % Tangent points and M computed analytically.
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6.5/0/B}
                        \tkzDefPoint(-0.385,0.923){T}
                        \tkzDefPoint(5.154,3.231){Tp}
                        \tkzDefPoint(5.538,2.308){M}
                        % Circles (drawn thin for context)
                        \tkzDefCircle[R](A,1) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                        \tkzDefCircle[R](B,3.5) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                        \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](A,cA)
                        \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](B,cB)
                        % Centre line (dashed)
                        \tkzDrawSegment[dashed, gray](A,B)
                        % Radii to tangent points
                        \tkzDrawSegments[thin](A,T B,Tp)
                        % Tangent segment TT' (prominent)
                        \tkzDrawSegment[very thick](T,Tp)
                        % Auxiliary dashed line AM parallel to TT'
                        \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](A,M)
                        % Right angle marks
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.18](A,M,B)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.14](Tp,T,A)
                        \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.14](T,Tp,B)
                        % Points
                        \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T,Tp,M)
                        \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                        \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                        \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T){$T$}
                        \tkzLabelPoint[above right](Tp){$T'$}
                        \tkzLabelPoint[right](M){$M$}
                        % Length labels
                        \tkzLabelSegment[below,font=\small](A,B){$d = 13$ cm}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[left,font=\small](A,T){$r{=}2$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[above,sloped,font=\small](T,Tp){$L = 12$ cm}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](B,M){$R{-}r{=}5$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](M,Tp){$r{=}2$}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
                By Pythagoras:
                <md>
                    <mrow> TT'^2 \amp= AB^2 - (R - r)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>       \amp= 13^2 - 5^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>       \amp= 169 - 25 </mrow>
                    <mrow>       \amp= 144 </mrow>
                    <mrow> TT'  \amp= 12 \text{ cm} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The length of the direct common tangent is <m>12</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-direct-tangent-find-d">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Two circles have radii 3 cm and 9 cm. The length of their direct common tangent is 8 cm. Find the distance between the centres.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let the distance between the centres be <m>d</m> cm. Using the direct common tangent length formula:
                <md>
                    <mrow> L^2 \amp= d^2 - (R - r)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> 8^2 \amp= d^2 - (9 - 3)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>  64 \amp= d^2 - 36 </mrow>
                    <mrow> d^2 \amp= 100 </mrow>
                    <mrow>   d \amp= 10 \text{ cm} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The distance between the centres is <m>10</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In each part, two circles are given. Using a compass and ruler, construct both direct common tangents. Mark the external centre of similitude <m>O</m> in each case.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Circle <m>A</m> with radius 1 cm, circle <m>B</m> with radius 3 cm, centres 6 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Circle <m>A</m> with radius 2 cm, circle <m>B</m> with radius 4 cm, centres 8 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Circle <m>A</m> with radius 1.5 cm, circle <m>B</m> with radius 3.5 cm, centres 7 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The diagrams below show the two completed direct common tangents for each
                configuration. Both tangent lines, when extended, meet at the external centre
                of similitude <m>O</m> on line <m>AB</m> extended beyond circle <m>A</m>.
            </p>
            <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="auto">
                <figure xml:id="fig-exer1a-direct">
                    <caption>Part (a): <m>r = 1</m>, <m>R = 3</m>, <m>d = 6</m> cm.</caption>
                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>
                            Two circles at A and B with two direct common tangents.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % r=1, R=3, d=6, scaled by 0.5: rA=0.5, rB=1.5, A=(0,0), B=(3,0)
                            % O = -r*d/(R-r) = -3, scaled: O=(-1.5,0)
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rA}{0.5}
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rB}{1.5}
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 3/0/B, -1.5/0/O}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rA) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rB) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                            % Tangent points via circle-on-diameter method
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,A) \tkzGetPoint{MA}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,B) \tkzGetPoint{MB}
                            \tkzInterCC(MA,A)(A,cA) \tkzGetPoints{T1}{T2}
                            \tkzInterCC(MB,B)(B,cB) \tkzGetPoints{T1p}{T2p}
                            \useasboundingbox (-0.7,-2.05) rectangle (4.8,2.05);
                            \clip (-0.7,-2.05) rectangle (4.8,2.05);
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,cA)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,cB)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](T1,T1p)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](T2,T2p)
                            \tkzDrawPoint(O)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](O){$O$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](B){$B$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <figure xml:id="fig-exer1b-direct">
                    <caption>Part (b): <m>r = 2</m>, <m>R = 4</m>, <m>d = 8</m> cm.</caption>
                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>
                            Two circles at A and B with two direct common tangents.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % r=2, R=4, d=8, scaled by 0.35: rA=0.7, rB=1.4, A=(0,0), B=(2.8,0)
                            % O = -r*d/(R-r) = -8, scaled: O=(-2.8,0)
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rA}{0.7}
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rB}{1.4}
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 2.8/0/B, -2.8/0/O}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rA) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rB) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,A) \tkzGetPoint{MA}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,B) \tkzGetPoint{MB}
                            \tkzInterCC(MA,A)(A,cA) \tkzGetPoints{T1}{T2}
                            \tkzInterCC(MB,B)(B,cB) \tkzGetPoints{T1p}{T2p}
                            \useasboundingbox (-0.9,-1.8) rectangle (4.4,1.8);
                            \clip (-0.9,-1.8) rectangle (4.4,1.8);
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,cA)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,cB)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](T1,T1p)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](T2,T2p)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](B){$B$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <figure xml:id="fig-exer1c-direct">
                    <caption>Part (c): <m>r = 1.5</m>, <m>R = 3.5</m>, <m>d = 7</m> cm.</caption>
                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>
                            Two circles at A and B with two direct common tangents.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % r=1.5, R=3.5, d=7, scaled by 0.5: rA=0.75, rB=1.75, A=(0,0), B=(3.5,0)
                            % O = -r*d/(R-r) = -5.25, scaled: O=(-2.625,0)
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rA}{0.75}
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rB}{1.75}
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 3.5/0/B, -2.625/0/O}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,\rA) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,\rB) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,A) \tkzGetPoint{MA}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,B) \tkzGetPoint{MB}
                            \tkzInterCC(MA,A)(A,cA) \tkzGetPoints{T1}{T2}
                            \tkzInterCC(MB,B)(B,cB) \tkzGetPoints{T1p}{T2p}
                            \useasboundingbox (-0.95,-2.15) rectangle (5.4,2.15);
                            \clip (-0.95,-2.15) rectangle (5.4,2.15);
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,cA)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,cB)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](T1,T1p)
                            \tkzDrawLine[add=0.5 and 0.5](T2,T2p)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](B){$B$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
        </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A direct common tangent <m>TT'</m> touches circle <m>A</m> (radius <m>r</m>) at <m>T</m> and circle <m>B</m> (radius <m>R</m>, <m>R \gt r</m>) at <m>T'</m>. The distance between the centres is <m>d = AB</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-exer2-proof-setup">
                    <caption>
                        Direct common tangent <m>TT'</m> and the auxiliary right triangle <m>ABM</m>,
                        where <m>AM \parallel TT'</m>.
                    </caption>
                    <image width="65%">
                        <shortdescription>
                            Two circles at A and B. A tangent line touches circle A at T and circle B
                            at T-prime. A dashed line from A parallel to TT-prime meets the line BT-prime
                            at M, forming right triangle ABM with the right angle at M.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85]
                            % Generic diagram: r=1, R=3.5, d=6.5 (symbolic labels only).
                            % O = -r*d/(R-r) = -2.6; tangent points computed analytically.
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 6.5/0/B, -2.6/0/O}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,1) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,3.5) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                            % Tangent points via circle-on-diameter
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,A) \tkzGetPoint{MA}
                            \tkzDefMidPoint(O,B) \tkzGetPoint{MB}
                            \tkzInterCC(MA,A)(A,cA) \tkzGetPoints{T}{Tx}
                            \tkzInterCC(MB,B)(B,cB) \tkzGetPoints{Tp}{Tpx}
                            % M: intersection of line through A parallel to TT', and line BT'
                            % M is on segment BT' at distance R-r from B.
                            % Direction B->Tp (unit vector): compute M = B + (R-r)/R * (Tp - B)
                            \tkzDefPointWith[linear,K={2.5/3.5}](B,Tp) \tkzGetPoint{M}
                            % Circles (thin)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](A,cA)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thin,gray](B,cB)
                            % Centre line
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed,gray](A,B)
                            % Radii
                            \tkzDrawSegments[thin](A,T B,Tp)
                            % Tangent TT' (prominent)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[very thick](T,Tp)
                            % Auxiliary AM (dashed)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](A,M)
                            % Right angle at M
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.22](A,M,B)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.16](Tp,T,A)
                            \tkzMarkRightAngle[size=0.16](T,Tp,B)
                            % Points
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B,T,Tp,M)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above left](T){$T$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[above right](Tp){$T'$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[right](M){$M$}
                            % Symbolic length labels
                            \tkzLabelSegment[below,font=\small](A,B){$d$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[left,font=\small](A,T){$r$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above,sloped,font=\small](T,Tp){$L = TT'$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](B,M){$R{-}r$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[right,font=\small](M,Tp){$r$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            From <m>A</m>, draw a line parallel to <m>TT'</m> meeting the line <m>BT'</m> at a point <m>M</m>. Explain why <m>BM = R - r</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Explain why triangle <m>ABM</m> is right-angled at <m>M</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Show that <m>AM = TT'</m>, and hence use Pythagoras' theorem to prove that
                            <md>
                                TT' = \sqrt{d^2 - (R - r)^2}.
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>AT \perp TT'</m>, <m>BT' \perp TT'</m>, and <m>AM \parallel TT'</m>, the quadrilateral <m>ATT'M</m> is a rectangle. Therefore <m>MT' = AT = r</m>, and so <m>BM = BT' - MT' = R - r</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>AM \parallel TT'</m> and <m>BT'</m> is perpendicular to <m>TT'</m>, the line <m>BM</m> is also perpendicular to <m>AM</m>. Therefore <m>\angle AMB = 90°</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>AMT'T</m> is a rectangle, <m>AM = TT'</m>. Applying Pythagoras to triangle <m>ABM</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> AB^2 \amp= AM^2 + BM^2 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> d^2  \amp= TT'^2 + (R-r)^2 </mrow>
                                    <mrow> TT'  \amp= \sqrt{d^2 - (R-r)^2}. </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In each part, find the length of the direct common tangent to the two circles.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 2 cm and 8 cm, centres 10 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 2 cm and 10 cm, centres 17 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 1 cm and 4 cm, centres 5 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 3 cm and 13 cm, centres 26 cm apart.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p>8 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p>15 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p>4 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p>24 cm</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In each part, find the distance between the centres of the two circles.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 1 cm and 9 cm, direct common tangent length 15 cm.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Radii 3 cm and 5 cm, direct common tangent length 4 cm.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li><p>17 cm</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>2\sqrt{5}</m> cm</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Explain why it is impossible to draw a direct common tangent when one circle lies entirely inside the other. What happens to the formula <m>L = \sqrt{d^2 - (R-r)^2}</m> in this case?
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-exer5-circle-inside">
                    <caption>
                        When <m>d \lt R - r</m>, circle <m>B</m> lies entirely inside circle <m>A</m>
                        and no direct common tangent exists.
                    </caption>
                    <image width="40%">
                        <shortdescription>
                            A large circle centred at A contains a smaller circle centred at B entirely
                            within it. A short dashed segment connects the two centres and is labelled d.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Outer circle A: center (0,0), radius 2.
                            % Inner circle B: center (0.5,0), radius 0.7.
                            % d = 0.5 &lt; R - r = 1.3, so B is inside A.
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 0.5/0/B}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,2) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,0.7) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,cA)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,cB)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above,font=\small](A,B){$d$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    When one circle lies inside the other, <m>d \lt R - r</m> (the distance between the centres is less than the difference of the radii). This means <m>d^2 - (R - r)^2 \lt 0</m>, so there is no real value of <m>L</m>. Geometrically, no straight line can be tangent to both circles while keeping both circles on the same side, because the inner circle always lies inside the outer one regardless of the direction of the line.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>
</section>
